---
import SiteLayout from '../../../components/SiteLayout.astro';

const title = 'What is the bus width on a graphics card?';
const description =
  'The memory bus defines how much data your GPU moves at once. A quick guide to what it is, why it matters and which number to pick.';

const fecha = 'June 12, 2026';
const dateISO = '2026-06-12';
const tiempoLectura = '4 min read';

const secciones = [
  { id: 'que-es', label: 'What is the memory bus?' },
  { id: 'como-funciona', label: 'How does it work?' },
  { id: 'bits-comunes', label: 'Most common values' },
  { id: 'ancho-vs-vram', label: 'Bus vs VRAM: which matters more?' },
  { id: 'rendimiento', label: 'Real impact in games' },
  { id: 'conclusion', label: 'Which bus to choose?' },
];
---

<SiteLayout title={`${title} | Monckey Gamer`} description={description} robots="index, follow" article={{ title, dateISO }}>
  <article class="post">
    <a class="category-back" href="/en/blog/">← Back to Blog</a>

    <header class="post-header">
      <span class="post-tag"><span class="post-tag-gg">GG</span> Gamer guide · Hardware</span>
      <h1>What is the bus width on a graphics card?</h1>
      <p class="post-lead">
        When you compare graphics cards you see numbers like "128-bit" or "256-bit" and nobody explains them well.
        The memory bus is one of the factors that most affects real performance, especially at high resolutions.
      </p>
      <div class="post-meta">
        <span>{fecha}</span>
        <span class="post-meta-dot"></span>
        <span>{tiempoLectura}</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <nav class="post-toc" aria-label="Article contents">
      <span class="post-toc-title">In this article</span>
      <ul>
        {secciones.map((s) => (
          <li><a href={`#${s.id}`}>{s.label}</a></li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </nav>

    <div class="post-body">
      <section id="que-es">
        <h2>What is the memory bus?</h2>
        <p>
          The <strong>memory bus</strong> (or bus width) is the "road" data travels on
          between the GPU and the VRAM. It is measured in bits: the wider it is, the more data can flow at the same time.
        </p>
        <p>
          Think of it as a highway: 128 bits is 4 lanes, 256 bits is 8 lanes. More lanes means
          more traffic flows without jams even when the speed limit is the same.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="como-funciona">
        <h2>How does it work in practice?</h2>
        <p>
          The memory bus, combined with the VRAM's speed, determines the
          <strong>memory bandwidth</strong>: the amount of data the GPU can read and write per second.
        </p>
        <p>
          Simplified formula: <code>Bandwidth = VRAM speed × Bus ÷ 8</code>. A GPU with
          GDDR6 at 18 Gbps and a 256-bit bus moves up to <strong>576 GB/s</strong>. With 128 bits, only 288 GB/s.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="bits-comunes">
        <h2>Most common values on current cards</h2>
        <div class="post-table-wrap">
          <table class="post-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Bus</th>
                <th>Typical segment</th>
                <th>What it's for</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>64 bits</td><td>Very basic entry</td><td>Office work and light video</td></tr>
              <tr><td>128 bits</td><td>Entry mid-range</td><td>1080p at medium-high settings</td></tr>
              <tr><td>192 bits</td><td>Mid-range</td><td>1080p ultra / 1440p</td></tr>
              <tr><td>256 bits</td><td>High end</td><td>Uncompromised 1440p–4K</td></tr>
              <tr><td>320+ bits</td><td>Flagship</td><td>4K ultra, professional editing</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="ancho-vs-vram">
        <h2>Bus vs amount of VRAM: which matters more?</h2>
        <p>
          Both matter, but in different ways:
        </p>
        <ul class="post-list">
          <li><strong>VRAM (GB)</strong> determines how much the GPU can store before needing more data.</li>
          <li><strong>The bus (bits)</strong> determines how fast it moves that data.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          You can have 16 GB of VRAM on a 128-bit bus and struggle at 4K because the "road" is narrow.
          Ideally both are balanced for your target resolution.
        </p>
        <p class="post-note">
          Tip: for competitive 1080p, 128 bits is enough. For 1440p or 4K, look for at least 192 bits.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="rendimiento">
        <h2>Real impact in games</h2>
        <p>
          The memory bus is especially noticeable in:
        </p>
        <ul class="post-list">
          <li>High-resolution textures (4K, mod packs).</li>
          <li>Ray tracing, which doubles the bandwidth demand.</li>
          <li>Open-world games with constant asset streaming.</li>
          <li>High-quality anti-aliasing (MSAA 4x or higher).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          In competitive shooters at low 1080p settings (CS2, Valorant), the bus matters less because
          textures are light and FPS depends more on the GPU and the processor.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="conclusion">
        <h2>Which bus to choose for your use case?</h2>
        <p>
          The practical rule for 2026 is simple: don't obsess over the number alone —
          look at the <strong>total bandwidth</strong> the VRAM type + bus combination delivers.
        </p>
        <p>
          An <a href="/en/graphics-cards/asus-dual-rtx-5060-8gb-oc-2/">RTX 5060</a> with GDDR7 and 128 bits
          can beat an older 256-bit GDDR5 card in bandwidth
          thanks to the higher speed of modern memory.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you want cards with a good balance of bus, VRAM and price,
          take a look at our <a href="/en/graphics-cards/">graphics cards</a> catalog.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <aside class="post-cta">
      <h3>Ready to upgrade your GPU?</h3>
      <p>Compare graphics cards with the bus and VRAM you need for your resolution.</p>
      <a class="btn" href="/en/graphics-cards/">View graphics cards</a>
    </aside>
  </article>
</SiteLayout>

<style>
  .post { max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .post-header { margin: 18px 0 32px; }
  .post-tag { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 7px; font-size: 0.68rem; font-weight: 500; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.14em; color: #8aa0b8; }
  .post-tag-gg { font-weight: 800; letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: #7cffcb; border: 1px solid rgba(124,255,203,0.3); border-radius: 5px; padding: 1px 5px; font-size: 0.62rem; }
  .post-header h1 { margin: 18px 0 16px; font-size: clamp(1.6rem,6vw,2.8rem); line-height: 1.15; overflow-wrap: break-word; }
  .post-lead { margin: 0 0 18px; color: #c8d8e8; font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.7; }
  .post-meta { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 12px; color: #8aa0b8; font-size: 0.9rem; }
  .post-meta-dot { width: 4px; height: 4px; border-radius: 50%; background: #8aa0b8; }
  .post-toc { margin: 0 0 40px; padding: 24px 28px; border-radius: 20px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); }
  .post-toc-title { display: block; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: #7cffcb; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .post-toc ul { margin: 0; padding: 0; list-style: none; display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2,minmax(0,1fr)); gap: 10px 24px; }
  .post-toc a { color: #c8d8e8; text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.95rem; transition: color 0.2s ease; }
  .post-toc a:hover { color: #7cffcb; }
  .post-body section { margin-bottom: 40px; scroll-margin-top: 24px; }
  .post-body h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; color: #e6f7ff; margin: 0 0 16px; padding-left: 14px; border-left: 3px solid #7cffcb; }
  .post-body p { color: #c8d8e8; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 16px; }
  .post-body strong { color: #e6f7ff; }
  .post-body code { background: rgba(27,183,255,0.12); color: #1bb7ff; padding: 2px 7px; border-radius: 6px; font-size: 0.9em; }
  .post-body a { color: #7cffcb; text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; }
  .post-list { margin: 0 0 16px; padding: 0; list-style: none; display: grid; gap: 12px; }
  .post-list li { color: #c8d8e8; line-height: 1.7; padding-left: 26px; position: relative; }
  .post-list li::before { content: ""; position: absolute; left: 4px; top: 11px; width: 7px; height: 7px; border-radius: 50%; background: #7cffcb; }
  .post-table-wrap { margin: 0 0 18px; overflow-x: auto; border-radius: 16px; border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); }
  .post-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  .post-table th { text-align: left; padding: 14px 20px; color: #7cffcb; font-size: 0.78rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.03); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); }
  .post-table td { padding: 13px 20px; color: #c8d8e8; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05); }
  .post-table tbody tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
  .post-table td:first-child { color: #e6f7ff; font-weight: 500; }
  .post-note { background: rgba(27,183,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(27,183,255,0.18); border-radius: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; color: #c8d8e8 !important; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  .post-cta { margin-top: 48px; padding: 36px; border-radius: 24px; text-align: center; background: linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(0,255,225,0.06),rgba(27,183,255,0.06)); border: 1px solid rgba(124,255,203,0.15); }
  .post-cta h3 { margin: 0 0 8px; font-size: 1.4rem; color: #e6f7ff; }
  .post-cta p { margin: 0 0 20px; color: #c8d8e8; }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .post-toc { padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 28px; }
    .post-toc ul { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .post-lead { font-size: 1rem; }
    .post-meta { flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 8px; }
    .post-body section { margin-bottom: 32px; }
    .post-body h2 { font-size: 1.3rem; }
    .post-body p { line-height: 1.7; }
    .post-table { font-size: 0.85rem; }
    .post-table th { padding: 11px 12px; font-size: 0.7rem; }
    .post-table td { padding: 10px 12px; }
    .post-cta { padding: 28px 20px; }
    .post-cta h3 { font-size: 1.25rem; }
    .post-cta .btn { width: 100%; }
  }
  @media (max-width: 380px) {
    .post-table th, .post-table td { padding: 9px 10px; font-size: 0.8rem; }
  }
</style>
